Title: ISN'T IT ROMANTIC - Official Trailer
Comment: I hope it's not all a coma dream! Come up with a more original and clever explanation. I do think it's worth noting that if the message of this movie is that the protagonist's obesity shouldn't handicap her, that message is clearly undermined as she exhibits the same preferences she implicitly or explicitly complains about. She's not interested in people that look like her herself, she wants a Hemsworth brother in top physical condition gifted with some of the world's most handsome genetics. That is, of course, the reality. Even those who are obese aren't attracted to obese bodies, because obesity is obviously unhealthy. So it's a justified bias, although it does unfortunately make life much more miserable for those afflicted with such a problem. They're not bad people, they just struggle with maintaining a healthier weight, and there are many reasons for it. Gluttony and very bad choices are far from the only reasons people find themselves severely overweight. I guess it just makes it truer (though sad) that the fat woman who feels invisible in her own fantasy world has made other fat people invisible. She also erases her own type of body. I think that's psychologically interesting and probably true about people's self-image, so I don't mind the depiction. Anyway, Rebel Wilson has talent, as do the supporting cast, and I really like the aesthetic. There are many similar movies, but this has the potential to be at the top of the heap, though competition is not that steep: Amy Schumer, _Shallow Hal_ , etc. If this gets good reviews I might see it! I'm a sucker for the Hollywood fantasy dreamscape. They've got a classic Technicolor musical influence going on here and I like it.
